<TITLE> Taiwan probe finds illegal sale to North Korea </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TAIPEI, Nov 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Taiwan authorities have found that a local company sold equipment for potential military use to North Korea in violation of United Nations sanctions, a spokesman for the island's investigation bureau said on Wednesday. The Taipei-based trading company, which media reports named as Yi Cheng, sold a set of filtration devices worth at least T$5 million ($155,000) to reclusive North Korea, which some countries see as a rogue state with aggressive military ambitions, the spokesman said. The filters can be used for production of nuclear energy and weapons. UN sanctions adopted in 2006 bar sales to North Korea and Iran of equipment that could serve military purposes. Although Taiwan is not a UN member, to cooperate internationally the island government also barred such sales. "According to our investigation, the company definitely sold these products to North Korea," said Lin Chin-chi, spokesman for the Justice Ministry's investigation bureau, which has turned the case over to prosecutors. "It's a violation of trade laws." Lin would not say when the sale took place or what North Korea might have done with the filters. The company could not be reached for comment. Taiwan investigators have checked two other local firms this year for possible illegal sales to North Korea, in addition to three suspicious sales to Iran and one to China, Lin sa
